  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol, which is chemically known as copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O), changes its color from blue to white upon heating due to the loss of water of crystallization. \n\nHere's what happens during the process:\n\n### Structure\n- In its hydrated form, copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate has five water molecules integrated into its crystal structure.\n- These water molecules are responsible for its characteristic blue color, as they form complexes with the copper ions and stabilize the color.\n\n### Heating Process\n- When heated, copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate loses its water molecules.\n- Upon losing the water of crystallization, the compound transitions to an anhydrous form, copper(II) sulfate (CuSO\u2084).\n- The anhydrous form is white because the copper ions no longer have water molecules to coordinate with, and the compound thus loses its blue coloration.\n\n### Color Change Explanation\n- **Hydrated Form (Blue):** The hydration involves water molecules that contribute to the electronic transitions in the copper ions, giving a blue appearance.\n- **Anhydrous Form (White):** Without those water molecules, the electronic environment changes, leading to the loss of the blue color.\n\nThis process is reversible. If you add water to the anhydrous copper(II) sulfate, it will rehydrate and regain its blue color.",
